               <h5 class="mb-0">Why do we need database management system?</h5><br>
               <p class="mb-0"><i class="fa fa-arrow-right text-primary me-2"></i><b>Data Organization :</b> DBMS helps
                  in organizing and structuring data efficiently. It provides a systematic way to store, manage, and
                  retrieve data.</p>
               <p class="mb-0"><i class="fa fa-arrow-right text-primary me-2"></i><b>Data Integrity :</b> DBMS ensures
                  data integrity by enforcing constraints and rules on the data. This helps in maintaining the accuracy
                  and consistency of the data stored in the database.</p>
               <p class="mb-0"><i class="fa fa-arrow-right text-primary me-2"></i><b>Data Security :</b> DBMS provides
                  features for controlling access to the data stored in the database. It allows administrators to define
                  user roles and permissions, ensuring that only authorized users can access and modify the data.</p>
               <p class="mb-0"><i class="fa fa-arrow-right text-primary me-2"></i><b>Data Concurrency :</b> In
                  multi-user environments, multiple users may need to access and modify the same data simultaneously.
                  DBMS manages concurrency control to ensure that transactions are executed in a controlled manner,
                  preventing data corruption and inconsistency.</p>
               <p class="mb-0"><i class="fa fa-arrow-right text-primary me-2"></i><b>Data Recovery :</b> DBMS provides
                  mechanisms for data backup and recovery in case of system failures or errors. It allows administrators
                  to restore the database to a previous consistent state, minimizing data loss.</p>
